<br>
When you add in med times, the numbers are indeed different.<br>
<br>
And Mage comes out ahead, as you admit you suspect.  <br>
<br>
The argument that recast time &quot;means nothing&quot; in long fights is NOT correct.  The opposite is true.  <br>
<br>
In addition just using standing regen times or even med rates (which will put the Mage ahead) is a flawed way to conduct a fair test.<br>
<br>
Your fight is &quot;fixed&quot;.  In the first place, the Mage and Enchanter won't be nuking like that anyway.  In the next, if they DID for some reason, then the Mage would be medding, worst case. *note that I say medding, worst case*<br>
<br>
Heck, the Chanter doesn't get done with his first mana load for almost a full minute behind the Mage, in your example.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> A full minute.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
How much mana do you think the Mage could get back in that time?   Be realistic.  No &quot;med rates&quot; or &quot;standing regen&quot;.<br>
<br>
I'll tell you. He could be back to FM, or nearly so, and blasting away again, at the same time the Chanter gets done blowing his first load.<br>
<br>
You seem to want to take the Chanter and Mage nukes into a Vacuum, look at the very most unrealistic comparison possible, and say Chanters have better DPS.<br>
<br>
Even if you analyze it using Meditation the Mage comes out ahead.<br>
<br>
You flatly state that in long fights recast time means nothing.  Let's take your spell, and add a second to the recast.  Does it matter now?  <br>
<br>
How about we add 30 seconds.  How about a minute.  Starting to matter, yet?<br>
<br>
How about if we add 2 minutes to the recast.  Suddenly it is obvious that recast time does matter.  Where did this miraculous change occur?  At what instant of recast delay?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Time Matters</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
<br>
Later, in a further statement, using &quot;all out burns&quot; you state flatly the Chanter will still come out ahead because &quot;you're going to leave out rains because of resist rates.&quot;<br>
<br>
That's bogus too.  Rains don't give the answer that suits you, so you conveniently remove them from analysis.<br>
<br>
Oh, better remove Firebolt of Tallon - it's not normal, you say.<br>
<br>
Get rid of rains, they get resisted.<br>
<br>
Med times not included BUT LOOK AT THIS DPS - you say.<br>
<br>
You are just picking and choosing your conditions to get answers you like.  No med rate.  No rains because &quot;of resist rates.&quot;  You want to be &quot;realistic&quot; about the resist rate (not really being realistic for a properly debuffed MOB), but not realistic about the kind of mana regen that could and would actually go on in a battle.  How convenient for your argument.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <br>
<br>
In addition, add the pet, if you REALLY want to compare spells.  The Mage pet ends up really skewing the results to absurdity.  The Mage pet may as well be considered as integral damage added to whatever current spell you're casting.<br>
<br>
You want to tailor your conditions to suit your claimed results. <br>
<br>
Your analyses, which keep making statements and conclusions, are self-admittedly incomplete, and once again, draw the wrong answer.  <br>
<br>
Context IS everything.  <br>
<br>
If you're going to do spell-to-spell comparison Damage/(mana*time) is the correct metric for spell analyses.  <br>
<br>
If you're going to really &quot;look at the facts, Jack,&quot; then pets matter.  Specialization matters.  Real mana recovery matters.  <br>
<br>
However, no matter WHICH way you do the analysis, the Mage is going to come out ahead, either slightly ahead in the Solovey Vacuum Continuum, or light years ahead, in real context.<br>
<br>
You really need to stop saying &quot;Here's my test and the results clearly show X but I haven't really looked at the whole thing.&quot;<br>
<br>
