<br>
From &quot;There exists X such that not P,&quot; you cannot conclude &quot;For all X not P.&quot;<br>
<br>
That is like saying, &quot;The President of the United States is not meant to wear a frilly dress, therefore Americans are not meant to wear frilly dresses.&quot;<br>
<br>
Just because one elemental, even the best elemental, is clearly designed not to be chain cast, does not mean that no elemental is meant to be chain cast.  In fact, the design of the class suggests otherwise.<br>
<br>
From the very beginning, mage pets have been extremely cheap to cast, both for mana and components.<br>
<br>
Specialization reduces the mana cost further.<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Spell Casting Mastery</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> reduces the mana cost even further.<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Summoning Efficiency</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> reduces the cost even further.<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Elemental Pact</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> allows mages to cast unlimited number of pets using one malachite.<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Quick Summoning 3</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> allows mages to summon pets in no more than 5 seconds.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Verant</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> gave me items and abilities that allow me to cast a pet in five seconds that costs 260 mana, and are faster than most of my nukes, and have a better damage to mana ratio than any nuke ever dreamt of by man, and which is effectively not limited by components.<br>
<br>
Hmmmm....what <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>will</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--> I do with this?<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Calebe:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  So if you want to refute it, argue with yourself.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I'm sorry, you don't get it either.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> &quot;I want this spell because I want this spell&quot;</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> is still not an argument.  All I am doing is agreeing that it would be a nice spell to have.  Just because it is a nice spell to have does not mean that you need it or deserve it, just that you want it.<br>
<br>
Using that logic, I could just as easily propose a 60th level componentless upgrade to the phantasmal armor line with double hitpoint and mana regeneration.  Wouldn't that be a nice spell too?  We could spend all day thinking of spells that would be nice to have, and would further our purposes in an obvious way.<br>
<br>
Proposing new cool spells is much easier than explaining why a spell is needed.<br>
