<br>
For an awful long time I was a devotee of the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>  vested pet model</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, where I lavished all the buffs and equipment I could on my pets and kept them alive.  Chaincasting went against my instincts.  But then, when I became frustrated at what I was limited to soloing at level 60, I gave chaincasting a shot.  And have been hooked on it ever since.<br>
<br>
Chaincasting, while not aesthetically pleasing to some, is clearly one of the most powerful tools in the mage arsenal.  Ignore it as you choose, but to deny its power is sheer folly.<br>
<br>
Before I started chaincasting, I was limited to soloing snakes and golems in the Gray.  Now, I mow down 55th level Sun Revenants with very little downtime (regenerating mana cannibalizing ms2 pets).<br>
<br>
As for the epic... I have no doubts whatsoever that it is the best single mage item available at this time.  Unfortunately, many mages are so blinded by the glory of the epic pet that they remind me of the proverb about a man with a hammer...that man will inevitably approach every problem as needing to be whacked with a hammer, even though there are more effective solutions not involving hammers.<br>
<br>
Stubbornly sticking to a one-size-fits-all solution to all your problems in Everquest is just as foolish as it is in real life.  Use your epic or vested pet.  But if you can do something better chaincasting, you're only holding yourself back if you don't do it. <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=363562">Shazar Oom <BR>
Arch Mage <BR>
